1. Host-to-Host Communication Patterns
Use Sysmon Event ID 3 (Network Connections).

Important fields to baseline:

Computer (source host)

DestinationIp

DestinationHostname

DestinationPort

Image (process making connection)

User

Protocol

Example baseline:

Source Host	Destination	Port	Process
WS01	DC01	88	lsass.exe
WS01	FILE01	445	explorer.exe
APP01	DB01	1433	sqlservr.exe
Why important:

Detect new connections

Detect new services

Detect unexpected lateral movement

This data is often analyzed in Splunk or Elastic Stack.

2. Domain Controller Communication Baseline
Domain controllers are the center of authentication traffic.

Baseline which hosts normally communicate with DC and on which ports.

Important DC ports:

Port	Protocol
88	Kerberos
389	LDAP
445	SMB
636	LDAPS
3268	Global Catalog
Baseline example:

Workstations → DC : Kerberos (88)
Servers → DC : LDAP (389)
Admin machines → DC : RDP (3389)
Anomalies to detect:

Workstations performing LDAP enumeration

Unknown host connecting to DC

PowerShell connecting to DC

3. User Authentication Patterns
From Windows Security logs.

Key Event IDs:

Event ID	Meaning
4624	Successful logon
4625	Failed logon
4648	Explicit credentials
4672	Admin privileges assigned
Fields to baseline:

Account_Name

Logon_Type

IpAddress

WorkstationName

Computer

Example baseline:

User	Source	Destination	Logon Type
jsmith	WS01	DC01	Network
admin1	ADMINPC	SERVER01	RDP
Abnormal patterns:

user logging into new machines

admin logins from workstation

service accounts interactive login

4. Process-to-Network Behavior
Sysmon provides process visibility.

Important fields:

Image

ParentImage

CommandLine

DestinationPort

DestinationIp

Example baseline:

Process	Network Usage
chrome.exe	internet
svchost.exe	DNS
